New @golfersjournal podcast: Developing Aimpoint took 100k lines of code. Hear the story of how it got boiled down to two fingers. Link in bio. 
—
In 2004, software developer Mark Sweeney was fed up with missing putts. So he dedicated two years of his life to creating a system that delivers perfect reads. He called it AimPoint. 
—
Viktor Hovland implemented it and won the Hero World Challenge. Keegan Bradley, Lydia Ko, Adam Scott and more now straddle their line and read their break in finger-widths. Hear from the inventor of this peculiar but effective strategy, as Sweeney and host Tom Coyne dig into something that took 100,000 lines of code to get right. Along the way, you’ll learn how Golf Channel’s virtual putting line came to be, how a group of third graders helped unlock an AimPoint mystery, and why you might already be a much better putter than you think.
—
#golf #podcast #instagolf #podcastersofinstagram #aimpoint #golfpodcast #putting

The Roman name for Scotland was Caledonia, and the ballad of that name remains my favorite pub song. A Scotsman gave the moniker to this stretch of South Carolina low country where many years later Mike Strantz would embark on his first solo build. I’d been wanting to visit Caledonia Golf & Fish Club for years and I Ioved every shot on the property. Quality from start to finish. With a fish shed and chowder and earnest hospitality. True Blue tmw…
—
#golf #golfcourse #golfcoursearchitecture #mikestrantz #southcarolina #pawleysisland #caledonia #caledoniagolfandfishclub #myrtlebeach #golfgetaway #golfstagram

As songs go, Caledonia has it all over True Blue. But as golf courses…I must say that Strantz seemed to spread his wings a bit more at the younger sibling. More bold notes on the blue side of the street. What’s your take?

Calusa climbs and views 😍

I’d played a lot of SW Fla during my Paper Tiger days—I’d seen the lakes and the gators and the grain—and wondered how good Calusa Pines could really be. Honestly, it’s better. It felt very far from any Florida I’d played before. The clubhouse felt like an old northeastern classic. The members were here for golf, not pickleball. And the course—massive earth was moved here, but you somehow don’t see it, even as you climb to heights that shouldn’t be here. Because you feel like you might be on a hillside in Georgia or on Long Island. Who knows? You just know you’re lucky as hell. 
—
Have a great 2023 all! Let’s play more and play better. See you out there. TC
—

As announced in today’s letter from our publisher @brendon_thomas I am humbled and honored to take on the role of Editor at The Golfer’s Journal. Watching what TGJ has become over the past seven years has been pure joy, with all thanks to our members who enable everything we do. We wouldn’t be around to thank anyone, however, if not for the talents and tireless efforts of Travis Hill, a friend and colleague who has guided TGJ from an idea to a publication read around the golf world. He has worn a hundred different hats for us and looked good in every one.

I’ll be working with Travis and our team to advance and evolve our mission of celebrating the game in all its forms and bringing our members an elevated storytelling experience—an antidote to the algorithm, as Brendon noted today.  

Thank you for this opportunity and challenge. I’m going to bust my ass to meet it.
 
Exciting days ahead @golfersjournal . We’d love for you to be a part of them: https://www.golfersjournal.com
